data.content:
Yes — in **MSTest 3.4+**, `DynamicData` supports **value tuples**, eliminating the `object[]` indirection:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What you get:**
- Compile-time type safety — no more silent `InvalidCastException` at runtime if you swap argument order or types.
- Named tuple elements improve readability in test explorer output.
- The test method signature is validated against the tuple arity/types.

If your data is all compile-time constants, `[DataRow]` is even simpler:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

Use `DynamicData` with tuples when your test data requires runtime construction (e.g., complex objects); use `[DataRow]` when all values are literals.
